The `debounce` function limits the rate at which a function can fire by delaying its execution until after a specified wait time has elapsed since the last time it was invoked.

```javascript
function debounce(func, wait) {
    let timeout;
    return function executedFunction(...args) {
        const later = () => {
            clearTimeout(timeout);
            func(...args);
        };
        clearTimeout(timeout);
        timeout = setTimeout(later, wait);
    };
}

// Example usage:
const saveInput = debounce(() => {
    console.log("Input saved!");
}, 1000);

// Simulating fast input changes
document.getElementById('inputField').addEventListener('input', saveInput);
```

In this example, when the user types in an input field, the `saveInput` function will only log "Input saved!" to the console once the user has stopped typing for 1 second.
